<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Advantageous Adventure Path, Part I (Sites 1 through 3)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.76)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495'>Devon "Devonator" Clark</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 12, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> You’ve read the articles.  You know the power of Pathfinder and Nelya.  You know what less experienced players have failed to learn--defining the path is a very powerful weapon.  But is that all?  What if the sites you define are the wrong sites?  Is denying your opponent his sites what’s really important?  Or is playing on the wrong sites possibly WORSE than playing on your opponent’s sites?  The answer is obvious--you need to play on the right sites!  But that begs the question, “What are the right sites?”  This article is the first of two that will attempt to answer that very important question, to explore the pros and cons of every site (through Realms of the Elf Lords) to help all players gain the most advantage from their adventure path  . . . <br />
<br />
(Author’s Note: Texts are paraphrased.)<br />
<br />
Site 1<br />
There are 3 sites in the game whose importance supercedes all others.  They are the most important; therefore extra consideration must be given to these sites.  Site 1 is the first of these sites AND the most important of them (the other two being sites 7 and 9).  Simply put, you must start off on the right foot, and picking the right site 1 will ensure that you do . . .<br />
<br />
Bag End: <br />
Exert a Hobbit to play The Gaffer from your draw deck.  <br />
Downloading the Gaffer can be an incredible boon to any deck that focuses on Frodo and/or Sam exertions.  Thus, he enables you to continually remove burdens (or anything else that might require Sam or Frodo exertions).  However, the difference between a bid of 5 and 7 is not nearly as great as the difference between 3 and 5, therefore the benefits may not outweigh the ability to download a companion or use a more beneficial Hobbit helping site 1.<br />
<br />
East Road: <br />
Each companion costs +2<br />
This is a site 1 that players play with no intention of starting it.  If you run very few companions and want to go second, chances are good that the East Road is the site for you.  Why?  Because if by some stroke of luck you end up going first, your opponent will think twice about playing companions on his turn because of the “East Road Tax”.  However, if you are playing a more balanced deck with companions that want to be played, the East Road Tax may be too much for you to justify starting it.<br />
<br />
Farmer Maggot’s Field: <br />
Exert a Hobbit to play Merry or Pippin from your draw deck.<br />
Contrary to popular opinion, Pippin and Merry are very strong companions.  And that makes the Fields start very underrated.  It takes away Green Dragon and Prancing Pony starts while giving you an advantage of 5 companions that most decks won’t account for.  The drawback is that playing both Merry and Pippin requires 2 exertions . . . and you might be lacking a stronger fighting companion at the early sites.<br />
<br />
Green Dragon Inn: <br />
Exert a Hobbit to play Sam from your draw deck.<br />
Perhaps the biggest argument for the Green Dragon Inn is that it wins tournaments.  By bidding high, pulling Sam, exerting Sam to remove burdens, and then killing Sam, you start in the lead in about 90% of your games, and then it’s just a matter of holding it.  Meanwhile, the start is just rare enough that most players won’t really prepare for it.  The drawback to this site is that if you end up with an all minion hand, having Sam as your only backup could lead to some serious trouble in the early game.<br />
<br />
Green Hill Country: <br />
Hobbits cost –1<br />
Green Hill Country’s text is best used with Hobbit Farmers.  By allowing your Hobbit friends to play for free (or in some cases 1), you twilight choke your opponent while your Hobbit Swarm becomes untouchable.  Furthermore, since this is typically played in a Hobbit fellowship, you can bid high to go first.  But, Hobbit Farmers take up valuable card slots in your deck because you need to pull them early and since your strategy will probably be ally centric, the Anduin Confluence can cause some serious problems.<br />
<br />
Hobbiton Party Field: <br />
Exert a Hobbit to play Bilbo from your draw deck.<br />
Many decks rely on Bilbo to support their hobbits or be their means of condition removal.  The Hobbiton Party Field is a little extra guarantee that you’ll get him by the time that you need him.  If used in conjunction with Practically Everybody Was Invited, you have an efficient means of getting Hobbit Allies from your deck in the order you need them.  The drawback is that, like most other site 1s, you don’t get to download another companion.  AND to truly make good use of Bilbo, you have to dedicate a lot of card slots to him.<br />
<br />
Hobbiton Woods: <br />
Exert a Hobbit to play your site 2.  <br />
This can be very useful in a Hobbit Deck that wants to stealth its way into site 3 on the very first turn.  It can also be a very appropriate defensive card by denying your opponent potentially threatening site 2s such as Weathertop or Midgewater Marshes.  The downside is that after the first turn, its usefulness is exhausted, so if you do not get other defensive cards, your fellowship is in trouble.<br />
<br />
Prancing Pony: <br />
Add a burden to play Aragorn from your draw deck.<br />
Aragorn is arguably the strongest fighting companion in the game, and that makes a Prancing Pony start often a no-brainer.  However, that is also one of its biggest drawbacks, and honestly there are quite a few.  First, the apparent no-brainer means that many players will not look at their other options to find a potentially more useful site 1.  Second, it adds a burden, meaning that the only truly safe bids for a Prancing Pony start are 0-2 (unless you sacrifice a fighting companion to play Sam in your starting fellowship); moreover it makes your fellowship susceptible to burdening strategies.  Third, the Pony breeds dependence in many players . . . take away the Pony and you’ll win games just by upsetting your opponent’s fellowship expectations.  Finally, the prerequisite low bid will often make you go second to a more aggressive opponent, and that can be a game-breaker.  Aside from these drawbacks, there is also a nested double-edged sword in a Prancing Pony start.  The shadow player is almost guaranteed 9+ twilight at site 2.  That translates into a lot of minion cards being played, which is a potentially dangerous situation if you’re the free people’s player.  However, if you’re the shadow player, it can also be good for you by allowing you to set up your shadow strategy.<br />
<br />
Shire Lookout Point: <br />
Spot Gandalf to play Gandalf’s Cart from your draw deck.<br />
With Gandalf’s Cart as a sort of pawn shop for Free People’s possessions, many daring LotR players can start the Lookout Point and generate massive amounts of throughput with their fellowship, which can potentially make both their shadow and fellowship sides unstoppable.  However, the immediate danger of the Shire Lookout Point is that if you lose the bid and go second, with only Gandalf and Frodo to start the game, important weapons clogging your hand, and no way to download companions, you could be in serious trouble.<br />
<br />
Town Center: <br />
Each time you play a Shire Ally, you may draw a card.<br />
The Rule of 4 has hindered this sites usefulness, but that doesn’t mean that it’s not useful.  This site compliments Hobbit Farmers very well, and any site that allows you to draw a card when meeting a certain condition can greatly improve your deck’s performance by allowing you access to the cards that you need.  The drawback to this site is that, like many others, it doesn’t allow you to download companions from your deck, which makes it subject to luck.  If you draw an all minion hand to begin the game, your fellowship could be in serious trouble at site 2.<br />
<br />
Westfarthing: This site can also be used with Hobbit Farmers.  The ability to reduce companion cost can be of great benefit to a twilight limiting fellowship.  The drawback is that this ability cannot be played in conjunction with any other cost reducing abilities.  That said, 1 twilight at site 2 will generally only translate into 1 wound at worst and often it won’t even do that.  In other words, this site gives away free wounds to the shadow player.<br />
<br />
Site 2<br />
Now that we’ve left home, we find ourselves coming to our first stop on our journey and evil’s first chance to steal the ring.  Often, this early in the game, it is best that we still help our fellowship get established, because most sides won’t accomplish much before site 3.  Moria is almost a guaranteed first-turn double move.  Still, site 2 is important for an effective deck, and I see many players taking note of a site’s text or shadow number, but not both together.  You must consider these two aspects as one . . . <br />
<br />
Bree Gate<br />
2--Spot a Ranger to make the move limit +1<br />
When used in conjunction with Rivendell Waterfall, your fellowship could get as far as site 5 on turn 1.  But in so doing, you skip the first sanctuary and limit your throughput (By getting all of the way to site 5 turn 1, you only give yourself 2 opportunities to draw fellowship cards before you really put yourself in harms way).  Furthermore, your opponent has the same opportunity, so if you draw an all fellowship hand, your opponent can get a near insurmountable lead to start the game.  <br />
<br />
Bree Streets<br />
1--You do not pay roaming penalties for Nazgul<br />
This site reduces the cost of all of your Nazgul by 2 (except for Ulaire Nelya).  To many, that makes it a better site 2 than the Weatherhills, which only reduces Nazgul cost by 1.  However, the text is deceptive.  Most Nazgul decks would benefit more from Weatherhills.  This site is used best in a Nazgul deck that goes first, because you would play Nelya, convert site 2, and make all of your Nazgul cheap thereafter.  If you plan to go second, Weatherhills is the better cost-reducing site.  <br />
<br />
Breeland Forest<br />
1--No Stealth events may be played here (Forest)<br />
Depending on how it is used, Breeland Forest can be either devastating or harmless.  It forces your opponent to hold Stealths (if he has any) until later sites, which can be either good or bad, as it will often be much more beneficial to you if your opponent plays them early so that they don’t have them when they need them.  On the other hand, the ability to force Hobbits to skirmish can single handedly win games if used in and against the right deck.  The drawback is that by securing site 2 against stealth events, you open yourself to A Ranger’s Versatility, which is often a bigger threat.<br />
<br />
Buckleberry Ferry<br />
1--If your fellowship consists of only hobbits, no skirmishes take place at Buckleberry Ferry.<br />
This card is the opposite of Breeland Forest.  It’s a hand full of free stealths at site 2 if you’re playing an all Hobbit deck.  This site combos well with Hobbiton Woods and can almost ensure a turn 1 double move for the right fellowship.  Meanwhile, it’s almost guaranteed that it won’t help your opponent.  Face it, you don’t see all Hobbit decks very often.  However, if your opponent IS playing all hobbits, you’ve given him a free site.  And the low shadow number limits the amount of cards you can play to effectively make use of your shadow’s opportunity.<br />
<br />
Ettenmoors<br />
2--Exert a minion or companion to make him strength +2 (Plain)<br />
The Ettenmoors text, when used in conjunction with the right shadow side, is potentially the most devastating site 2 of the lot as you can force your opponent to exert (i.e., take wounds) just to keep his companions alive.  Then, having done multiple wounds, your opponent will stop rather than risk facing those minions again.  The downside is that it’s a double-edged sword, as your opponent can do the same.<br />
<br />
Midgewater Marshes<br />
1--When the fellowship moves to Midgewater Marshes, all Hobbit companions must exert (Marsh)<br />
This is the site 2 of choice for a Sauron Direct Damage deck or a Moria Archery deck because exertions, regardless of whether they are on a fighting companion or non-fighting companion, equate to extra wounds; and extra wounds mean that it is harder to heal completely at sanctuaries.  But, again, you must move there as well.<br />
<br />
Midgewater Moors<br />
1--Whenever you play a minion, the free people’s player must discard a card from hand (Plain)<br />
This is the site 2 of choice for a discard themed deck.  Of course, like many others, this site is a double-edged sword.  If you play this site, chances are good that you’re going second, so considering that you’re going to force your opponent to discard cards of their choosing from hand, your opponent will get to reload his hand, which will probably lead him to an extra minion or two.  Expect to discard 3 or 4 cards during your turn.  And those few discards could be game altering.<br />
<br />
Trollshaw Forest<br />
1--When you play a free people’s possession or artifact, you may draw a card (Forest)<br />
Another site that allows you to draw cards when meeting a certain criterion!  Trollshaw has a low twilight number so your opponent won’t be able to drop loads of shadow on you, and if your opponent forces you to stay, it can only help your deck set up faster.  Trollshaw forest can be a great benefit to any fellowship or shadow side that takes time to set up, as it will help your deck’s throughput immensely.  The drawbacks of this site are that to truly utilize this site’s text, you must stop, and that means that your opponent could pass you or, even worse, pull away.  Conversely, another drawback to the site is that many players are too wary of falling behind to stop and actually use the Forest’s text.  I have found in some decks that stopping at Trollshaw will ensure victory because of those few extra cards.  Also, this site is a forest, which makes it the domain of A Ranger’s Versatility.<br />
<br />
Weatherhills<br />
3--Nazgul cost -1<br />
As mentioned earlier, Weatherhills is a better choice for site 2 in Nazgul decks that go second.  Nazgul decks do not swarm, and it is very rare for any Nazgul deck to get more than 3 minions out at site 2, much less 3 roaming minions since the good Nazgul decks tend to play very few Nerteas, Osteas, or Lemenyas.  This means that if a Nazgul is roaming, he’s either Ulaire Cantea or costs 6+.  Hence, you won’t get 3 minions out unless 1 of them is Ulaire Nelya.  That said, with a shadow number 2 higher than Bree Streets and its cost reduction, the first 2 roaming Nazgul are paid for.  Then, on top of that, it also reduces Nelya’s cost, compliments Bill Ferny’s text, and provides extra twilight for cards such as Black Breath or Beauty is Fading.  The drawback to this site is that most decks that play Weatherhills rely on your fellowship going second, which can be the difference between victory and defeat, especially when you consider that most Nazgul players will stop here just to be able to play the Ford of Bruinen.<br />
<br />
Weathertop<br />
3--All Nazgul at Weathertop are fierce<br />
This site is really only fits into a Twilight Nazgul strategy, because a fierce Twilight Witch King or Enquea at site 2 can be game breaking.  Thus, the strength of this site is that, as I said, if you get the Twilight King or Enquea here, you can just about guarantee the win.  The downside is that if you don’t, you can just about guarantee a loss.  This site is very prone to luck of the draw, but when it works, it’s nearly unstoppable.<br />
<br />
Site 3<br />
The first of 2 sanctuaries and the reason that many players consider sites 2 and 3 safe!  With a twilight number of 0 and only 2 shadow phase prior to the sanctuary’s healing, most decks heal completely here.  That is why many people believe that you can double move first turn no matter what the situation.  Of course, you must still take caution, as many good shadow sides will capitalize on other players’ over-eagerness to double-move.  Also, many of these Sites have the “Play to Draw” text . . . and 1 card at an early site can theoretically translate to 10+ extra cards by the end of the game.  That’s a difference maker.<br />
<br />
Council Courtyard<br />
0--When the fellowship moves from the Council Courtyard, remove 2 twilight<br />
The Council Courtyard is a staple of twilight limiting decks; however it is important to understand that those 2 are removed before the twilight cost for the move is paid.  Therefore, unless you’re skipping the sanctuary, you only get to remove twilight from cards played in the fellowship phase.  Of course, that is still a very strong effect, as often you won’t get all of the cards that you need in your first turn, so you’ll often have cards to play there.  The downside is that your opponent gets to use the text as well, and 2 twilight can be the difference between a Troll at Site 4 and no Troll.<br />
<br />
Frodo’s Bedroom<br />
0--Play a Hobbit to draw a card<br />
Frodo’s Bedroom is the obvious choice for any Hobbit-centric deck.  It allows you to set up an Ally intensive Hobbit side much quicker.  Plus, as mentioned, just 1 extra card at Site 3 “can” mean 10 extra cards in the long run.  And since the majority of decks are not Hobbit intensive, Frodo’s Bedroom will rarely help your opponent.  The drawbacks to this site are that in order to use the text, you have to play cards, and that typically means that you’re adding to the pool as you go on to the most dangerous sites.  Also, this site does not work in conjunction with Town Center (assuming that you are using Hobbit Farmers), because both are fellowship phase actions.<br />
<br />
Ford of Bruinen<br />
0--The first Nazgul played at the Ford of Bruinen costs –5 (River)<br />
The mere threat of the Ford can stop an opposing fellowship from making a second move.  After all, the Ford basically allows you to play a Nazgul for free, and additional Nazgul are ALWAYS dangerous.  Also note that the Ford’s text is not a Shadow action, so it does work with Morgul Gates.  Furthermore, it only affects the first Nazgul played “at” the Ford.  So, you could play Nelya at the Council Courtyard for 5, convert the site, and your next Nazgul will cost –5, even though one Nazgul was already there.  The downside of this site is that it’s a River, which means that you have to worry about A Ranger’s Versatility.  <br />
<br />
House of Elrond<br />
0--When the fellowship moves here, spot 2 Elves to remove a burden<br />
This site can counteract the effects of the Prancing Pony or provide relief for an aggressive bid.  Unless you’re playing a burden intensive shadow strategy, this site 3 doesn’t hurt you, but it doesn’t really help you, either (especially when compared to a Rivendell Valley or Council Courtyard, for instance).  It’s really a neutral site.  Of course, it’s value could increase as more burdening strategies are added to the game.<br />
<br />
Rivendell Valley<br />
0--Play an Elf to draw a card<br />
It would seem that this is an obvious choice for an Elf intensive deck, however that might not be the case.  Many elf-centered decks rely on Galadriel to play their elves for free.  Well, if a free elf leading to extra cards seems too good to be true, that’s because it is.  Both the Valley’s text and Galadriel’s text are fellowship phase actions, so you have to choose if you want that elf to be free or allow you to draw an extra card.  And for that reason, it might be more beneficial to you to play the Council Courtyard or House of Elrond.  On the other hand, in many games, you might not have found your copies of Galadriel, so you might get use out of its text.  In short, this site can benefit you by allowing you to draw extra cards, but the cards that you will likely play to do it (Elrond, Galadriel, Calaglin, etc.) work in strategies that will often benefit you in some other way that supercedes the Valley’s text.<br />
<br />
Rivendell Terrace<br />
0--Play a Man to draw a card<br />
Ironically, the Terrace belongs more in Gandalf decks than it does in Gondor decks.  Barliman, Dreary, Hugin, et al., are all men.  There are more men in the Gandalf Culture than there are in the Gondor culture, and that’s a common misconception.  For that reason, the Terrace doesn’t suffer the fellowship action contradictions that the Valley or Frodo’s Bedroom do (of course, there is A Wizard Is Never Late), so it’s usually a safer choice.  However, there aren’t many all-Man decks that are tournament viable yet; so it might be more worthwhile to play the House of Elrond or Council Courtyard..<br />
<br />
Rivendell Waterfall<br />
0--Spot a Ranger to make the move limit +1 (Forest)<br />
For the most part, I covered the pros and cons of this site when I covered the Bree Gate.  However, there are a few subtle differences.  This site is a forest, so shadow sides are susceptible to ARV.  That’s both good and bad.  This site is a Sanctuary, so whereas site 2 suggests that you will skip a Sanctuary to use it, the Waterfall (if you start your turn there) can take you from sanctuary to sanctuary in 1 turn.  That makes it a better choice than site 2, because it doesn’t involve you skipping sanctuaries.  However, if you do try to use this site to support a triple move, you’re going to have to move through the Bridge.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Well, we have reached the end of the first leg of our journey across the Advantageous Adventure Path.  Join me next time when we will explore the Mines of Moria, Lothlorien Woods, and Anduin River.  Until then, this is your tour-guide saying that I hope you’ve enjoyed our expedition through Middle-Earth, and I hope you’ve discovered the beauty and dangers of some of the most spectacular locations in all of our imaginations.<br />
<br />
Well, sorry about the textbook serial-documentary sendoff.  I hope you enjoyed the article, and I hope it was helpful.  There’s still more to come . . . <br />
<br />
Devon “Lifestyles of the Short and Hairy-Footed” Clark<br />
